# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-phoenix
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] HBase features compression, in-memory operation, and Bloom filters on a per-column basis as outlined in the original Bigtable paper.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] Tables in HBase can serve as the input and output for MapReduce jobs run in Hadoop, and may be accessed through the Java API but also through REST, Avro or Thrift gateway APIs.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] HBase is a wide-column store and has been widely adopted because of its lineage with Hadoop and HDFS.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] HBase runs on top of HDFS and is well-suited for fast read and write operations on large datasets with high throughput and low input/output latency.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] HBase is not a direct replacement for a classic SQL database, however Apache Phoenix project provides a SQL layer for HBase as well as JDBC driver that can be integrated with various analytics and business intelligence applications.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] The Apache Trafodion project provides a SQL query engine with ODBC and JDBC drivers and distributed ACID transaction protection across multiple statements, tables and rows that use HBase as a storage engine.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] HBase is now serving several data-driven websites but Facebook's Messaging Platform migrated from HBase to MyRocks in 2018.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] Unlike relational and traditional databases, HBase does not support SQL scripting; instead the equivalent is written in Java, employing similarity with a MapReduce application.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] In the parlance of Eric Brewer's CAP Theorem, HBase is a CP type system.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] Apache HBase began as a project by the company Powerset out of a need to process massive amounts of data for the purposes of natural-language search.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] Since 2010 it is a top-level Apache project.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] Facebook elected to implement its new messaging platform using HBase in November 2010, but migrated away from HBase in 2018.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-hbase] The 2.5.x series is the current stable release line, it supersedes earlier release lines.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-phoenix] Phoenix began as an internal project by the company salesforce.com out of a need to support a higher level, well understood, SQL language.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-phoenix] It was originally open-sourced on GitHub on 28 Jan 2014 and became a top-level Apache project on 22 May 2014.
[src:apache-phoenix/apache-phoenix] Apache Phoenix is included in the Cloudera Data Platform 7.0 and above, Hortonworks distribution for HDP 2.1 and above, is available as part of Cloudera labs, and is part of the Hadoop ecosystem.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Please note that each optional element in the URL requires all previous optional elements.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] For example, to specify the HBase root ZNode, the ZooKeeper port *must* also be specified.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] There are a number of keys exposed for client-use.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The most commonly-used keys are: `url` and `serialization`.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The `url` key is required to interact with the Phoenix Query Server.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] CSV data can be bulk loaded with built in utility named `psql`.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Typical upsert rates are 20K - 50K rows per second (depends on how wide are the rows).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] You can create both a Phoenix table or view through the `CREATE TABLE`/`CREATE VIEW` DDL statement on a pre-existing HBase table.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] In both cases, we'll leave the HBase metadata as-is.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] For `CREATE TABLE`, we'll create any metadata (table, column families) that doesn't already exist.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] We'll also add an empty key value for each row so that queries behave as expected (without requiring all columns to be projected during scans).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The other caveat is that the way the bytes were serialized must match the way the bytes are serialized by Phoenix.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] For `VARCHAR`, `CHAR`, and `UNSIGNED_*` types, we use the HBase `Bytes` methods.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The `CHAR` type expects only single-byte characters and the `UNSIGNED` types expect values greater than or equal to zero.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] For signed types (`TINYINT`, `SMALLINT`, `INTEGER` and `BIGINT`), Phoenix will flip the first bit so that negative values will sort before positive values.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Because HBase sorts row keys in lexicographical order and negative value's first bit is 1 while positive 0 so that negative value is 'greater than' positive value if we don't flip the first bit.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] So if you stored integers by HBase native API and want to access them by Phoenix, make sure that all your data types are `UNSIGNED` types.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Our composite row keys are formed by simply concatenating the values together, with a zero byte character used as a separator after a variable length type.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] then you have an HBase table with a name of `t1` and a column family with a name of `f1`.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Remember, in HBase, you don't model the possible `KeyValue`s or the structure of the row key.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This is the information you specify in Phoenix above and beyond the table and column family.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The `pk` column declares that your row key is a `VARCHAR` (i.e. a string) while the `"f1".val` column declares that your HBase table will contain `KeyValue`s with a column family and column qualifier of `"f1":VAL` and that their value will be a `VARCHAR`.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Note that you don't need the double quotes if you create your HBase table with all caps names (since this is how Phoenix normalizes strings, by upper casing them).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Starting with Phoenix version 2.1, Phoenix supports index over mutable and immutable data.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Note that Phoenix 2.0.x only supports Index over immutable data.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Index write performance index with immutable table is slightly faster than mutable table however data in immutable table cannot be updated.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The secondary index won't be used unless all columns used in the query are in it ( as indexed or covered columns).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] All columns making up the primary key of the data table will automatically be included in the index.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Index would not be used in this case as `lastname` is not part of indexed or covered column.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This can be verified by looking at the explain plan.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] To fix this create index that has either `lastname` part of index or covered column.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Full table scan of 100M rows usually completes in 20 seconds (narrow table on a medium sized cluster).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This time come down to few milliseconds if query contains filter on key columns.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] For filters on non-key columns or non-leading key columns, you can add index on these columns which leads to performance equivalent to filtering on key column by making copy of table with indexed column(s) part of key.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The aggregation will be done in a coprocessor on the server-side, collapsing the amount of data that gets returned back to the client rather than returning it all.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Specify the principal and corresponding keytab in the JDBC URL as show above.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] By default, Phoenix lets HBase manage the timestamps and just shows you the latest values for everything.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] However, Phoenix also allows arbitrary timestamps to be supplied by the user.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] By specifying a `CurrentSCN`, you're telling Phoenix that you want everything for that connection to be done at that timestamp.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Note that this applies to queries done on the connection as well - for example, a query over `myTable` above would not see the data it just upserted, since it only sees data that was created before its `CurrentSCN` property.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This provides a way of doing snapshot, flashback, or point-in-time queries.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Keep in mind that creating a new connection is *not* an expensive operation.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The same underlying `HConnection` is used for all connections to the same cluster, so it's more or less like instantiating a few objects.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] RANGE SCAN means that only a subset of the rows in your table will be scanned over.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This occurs if you use one or more leading columns from your primary key constraint.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Query that is not filtering on leading PK columns ex.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] `select * from test where pk2='x' and pk3='y';` will result in full scan whereas the following query will result in range scan `select * from test where pk1='x' and pk2='y';`.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Note that you can add a secondary index on your `pk2` and `pk3` columns and that would cause a range scan to be done for the first query (over the index table).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] DEGENERATE SCAN means that a query can't possibly return any rows.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] If we can determine that at compile time, then we don't bother to even run the scan.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] SKIP SCAN means that either a subset or all rows in your table will be scanned over, however it will skip large groups of rows depending on the conditions in your filter.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] We don't do a SKIP SCAN if you have no filter on the leading primary key columns, but you can force a SKIP SCAN by using the `/*+ SKIP_SCAN */` hint.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Under some conditions, namely when the cardinality of your leading primary key columns is low, it will be more efficient than a FULL SCAN.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] No, it is not necessary to pool Phoenix JDBC Connections.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Phoenix's Connection objects are different from most other JDBC Connections due to the underlying HBase connection.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The Phoenix Connection object is designed to be a thin object that is inexpensive to create.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] If Phoenix Connections are reused, it is possible that the underlying HBase connection is not always left in a healthy state by the previous user.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] It is better to create new Phoenix Connections to ensure that you avoid any potential issues.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Implementing pooling for Phoenix could be done simply by creating a delegate Connection that instantiates a new Phoenix connection when retrieved from the pool and then closes the connection when returning it to the pool (see PHOENIX-2388).
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The empty or dummy `KeyValue` (with a column qualifier of `_0`) is needed to ensure that a given column is available for all rows.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] As you may know, data is stored in HBase as `KeyValue`s, meaning that the full row key is stored for each column value.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This also implies that the row key is not stored at all unless there is at least one column stored.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] Now consider JDBC row which has an integer primary key, and several columns which are all null.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] In order to be able to store the primary key, a KeyValue needs to be stored to show that the row is present at all.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This column is represented by the empty column that you've noticed.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] This allows doing a `SELECT * FROM TABLE` and receiving records for all rows, even those whose non-pk columns are null.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] The same issue comes up even if only one column is null for some (or all) records.
[src:apache-phoenix/faq] A scan over Phoenix will include the empty column to ensure that rows that only consist of the primary key (and have null for all non-key columns) will be included in a scan result.
